The Order is comprised of over 133 Chapters across the nation and supports programs including youth leadership and the Reserve Officers Training Corps (ROTC).

title: Korean War Veterans Association

title: Gold Star Wives of America, Inc.
content: Provides service, support and friendship to the widows and widowers of military personnel who died on active duty or as the result of a service connected cause. Also assists members in understanding and obtaining VA, DoD and other benefits.

title: Veterans Assistance Foundation (VAF)

title: Military Chaplains Association of the USA

title: African American Post Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) Association

title: American Defenders of Bataan & Corregidor

title: Armed Forces Services Corporation (AFSC)

title: American Gold Star Mothers, Inc.

title: American Red Cross  - Services for Military Members & Families

title: Non Commissioned Officers Association (NCOA)

title: Pearl Harbor Survivors Association, Inc.

Pledged to foster true American patriotism, social and welfare activities for all members, allegiance to the United States Government, and its flag, and to perpetuate the traditions and history of the Americal Division of the United States Army.

Serves the families and survivors of the seven uniformed services through education, information and advocacy. Issues include medical and dental
benefits, dependent education, retiree and survivor benefits, relocation and spouse employment.

title: Air Compassion for Veterans (ACV)

title: Project Compassion
content: Provides an original oil painting of a fallen loved one as a way to say "Thank you" to those Service Members who have given the ultimate sacrifice for America.

title: Gifts to Army
content: Provides information on the many different ways citizens, organizations and corporations can contribute cash or goods and services to benefit soldiers and their families.  Contact the Army Gift Program Coordinator.

title: Healing Heroes Network
content: Provides financial assistance for medical care to service members injured in the line of duty in Iraq or Afghanistan since Sept. 11, 2001. Treats wounded warriors for services delayed, not covered, or not approved under U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs benefit systems free of charge, including Hyperbaric Oxygen Therapy Treatment (HBOT), massage therapy, chiropractic therapy and more.

title: Wounded Warrior Project (WWP) Packs
content: Help a hero in need by purchasing a WWP Pack that will be presented to an injured Service Member recuperating in a military hospital. WWP Packs are filled with essential care and comfort items such as clothing, toiletries, playing cards and more.

title: A Million Thanks
content: Campaign to show appreciation through letters, e-mails, cards, prayers and thoughts.

title: U.S. Wounded Soldiers Foundation
content: Provides for the personal, family and rehabilitation support needs of combat Veterans deployed in Iraq and Afghanistan.

title: Wounded Heroes Foundation
content: Assists severely injured Service Members with physical, emotional and financial support, such as paying a missing mortgage payment, purchasing an accessible van, building or remodeling homes, securing a new mortgage at a lower interest rate and more.

title: Free Call Days - Operation Uplink
content: Phone cards for Service Members and hospitalized Veterans who are separated from those they care about. Request a card and Free Call Schedule lists dates when the free call service is available.

title: Armed Services Blood Program
content: Be a donor and give sick or injured troops and their families a second chance. Find out where to give blood.

title: Books for Soldiers
content: Ships books, DVDs and supplies to deployed soldiers and Veterans in VA hospitals.

title: Military Exchange Gift Certificates
content: Gifts from the Homefront  are redeemable at the Army & Air Force Exchange Service (AAFES), the Marine Corps Exchange (MCX), the Navy Exchange (NEX) and the Coast Guard Exchange.

title: Operation USO Care Package
content: Sponsor a care package and include a personal message to improve the lives of deployed troops around the world.

title: To Our Soldiers
content: Post a message to OIF/OEF service members.

title: Give 2 the Troops
content: Supports the physical, moral, and spiritual health of America's Armed Forces in combat zones through the letters and packages prepared and shipped by caring individuals.

title: Operation Troop Aid
content: Provides care-packages to deployed Service Members through donations and concert ticket revenues.

title: Navy Safe Harbor Foundation (NSHF)
content: Supports the recovery of seriously wounded, ill, and injured Sailors, Coast Guardsmen, and their families.

title: Freedom Alliance
content: Outreach and support to Service Members injured in combat and recuperating at military hospitals throughout the United States and currently serving on the frontlines.

title: Quilts of Valor
content: Creates quilts for combat wounded and injured Service Members from the War on Terror, including both physical and psychological wounds.

title: Hero to Hero
content: Troop morale support program that coordinates emergency first responder agency members sending their personal shirts (hats and more), bearing department logos to desert-deployed U.S. troops.

title: Any Soldier
content: Learn what, where, and how to send care packages and letters to deployed Service Members.

title: Defenders of Freedom
content: Helps troops currently deployed around the world though "support boxes" and provides support to the families of wounded soldiers.

title: Blue Star Museums
content: Learn about this collaborative program of the National Endowment of the Arts and Blue Star Families that offers free admission to museums for all active duty military personnel and their families during the summer.

title: Operation Second Chance
content: Supports Veterans and their families while they recover in military hospitals.  Efforts include building relationships, supporting immediate needs and interests and promoting awareness of the sacrifices made by our Armed Forces.

title: Operation Injured Soldiers
content: Raises funds for injured soldiers by engaging individuals and corporations in a variety of events and programs.

title: Operation Gratitude
content: Provides care packages to troops. Packages contain food, toiletries, entertainment items and personal letters of appreciation.

title: How Communities Can Support Military Children & Families
content: Discusses how communities can support the children and families of those serving in the military.

title: Operation Never Forgotten
content: Connects military and civilian worlds together using billboard galleries, public service announcements, photos and online networking.

title: Support Our Troops
content: Provides Service Members with care packages, positive public support, kids' camp assistance and other special events.

title: K9 Soldiers
content: Provides support to military working dogs and their handlers.

title: Picture A Hero
content: Offers free individual and family portraits to members of the military who are preparing to deploy.

title: Support America's Armed Forces
content: Supports military personnel by raising funds, collecting care package items and issuing grants to military bases, Veterans organizations or families to care for service personnel.

title: Adopt A Chaplain
content: Sends care packages to military chaplains serving in the Middle East and they distribute the items to the troops.

title: Joining Forces
content: White House program that asks Americans to get involved in supporting our military's needs in employment, education, wellness and public awareness. Learn how to get involved.

title: America's Adopt A Soldier
content: Connects soldiers, Veterans and their family members with local events to support the community. Activities include creating care packages and workshops to address mental health and employment issues.

title: Operation Interdependence
content: Provides a way for community members to support troops serving on the frontlines, military families and Veterans by sending care packages to troops overseas.

title: American Warrior - Making a Patriotic Difference
content: Dedicated to bringing World War II Veterans to see the World War II Memorial in Washington D.C.  Also brings these heroes to schools, senior centers and other fraternal organizations.

title: Adoptaplatoon.org
content: Supports American military personnel overseas by providing an on-going mail support system and sending comfort items in care packages overseas. AdoptaPlatoon also serves injured troops through the AAP Walking Wounded Project.

title: Gameday for Heroes
content: Sends wounded and Active Duty military personnel to college sporting events, focusing mainly on football, basketball and baseball.

title: Goodies-4-Grunts
content: Provides support for deployed soldiers in the form of care packages. Find information about what items are needed and how you can help.

title: Wreaths Across America
content: Oversees programs to remember and honor the service and sacrifices of our Veterans, Service Members and their families.

title: Gary Sinise Foundation
content: Provides an opportunity for people to give back by honoring our defenders, Veterans, first responders, their families and those in need. Creates and supports programs designed to entertain, educate, inspire, strengthen and build communities.

title: Veteran Tickets Foundation
content: Thanks Service Members and Veterans for their service by providing free tickets to sporting and entertainment events.

title: Yellow Ribbon Foundation
content: Provides assistance to military families with unmet needs, including education, medical and clothing.

title: Project EverGreen's GreenCare for Troops
content: Volunteers provide free lawn and landscape services for military families nationwide. To use this service register with Project EverGreen's GreenCare for Troops program.

title: Wounded Soldiers Wish
content: An initiative from A Million Thanks, Wounded Soldiers Wish seeks to raise funds to grant the wishes of recovering Service Members.

title: Freedom Is Not Free
content: Supporting the military and Veteran community, this organization makes grants for immediate financial needs, home modification and supports community projects helping the military and Veteran communities.

title: Military Children's Charity, Inc.
content: Distributes gifts collected for Service Member's children through the Family Readiness Programs set up by the individual military service branches. Gifts include holiday toys, theme park tickets, school supplies, baby items, and anything else that helps appropriately acknowledge military children.

title: Centers for Independent Living (CILs)
content: State by state list of CILs, which are private, non-profit organizations that provide services relating to employment, health care and living skills that support the independence of individuals with disabilities.

title: Home Front Hearts
content: Serves the families that serve our country by providing support and resources to the families of Service Members, increasing public awareness of the struggles and sacrifices of military families, and engaging both individuals and businesses in building communities that are responsive to the needs of these families.

title: United We Serve - Volunteer Opportunities
content: A nationwide service initiative that allows individuals to not only find volunteer opportunities in their community, but also to create their own. The VA offers several volunteer opportunities at varying VA facilities nationwide.  This site is managed by the Corporation for National and Community Service.

title: VA Voluntary Service Programs
content: Information on the VA Voluntary Service (VAVS), which allows volunteers to provide services to Veterans through numerous programs, including the Student Volunteer Program at VA medical centers, National Salute to Veteran Patients, Volunteer Transportation Network and Corporate Volunteerism. Click here if you are interested in volunteering or making a donation. Read the 2010 VAVS Annual Report.

title: American Red Cross  - Services for Military Members & Families
content: Provides emergency communications that link Service Members with their families back home, access to financial assistance, counseling, referral to community resources and assistance to Veterans.

title: United States Welcome Home Foundation
content: Support network of local, state and national community members and organizations that assists with the reintegration of warriors into their family, home and community.

title: American Legion - Heroes to Hometowns Program
content: Welcomes home Service Members who can no longer serve in the military and establishes a support network allowing them and their families to ease into their hometown or new surroundings. Sign up online for assistance.

title: Center for Mental Health Services (CMHS) Services Locator
content: Provides comprehensive information about mental health services and resources for professionals, consumers and their families, and the public. Search by selecting a state or U.S. territory.

title: Network of Care
content: Provides links to community treatment services for mental and behavioral health, including support groups and other community services for the following states: California, Connecticut, Iowa, Maryland, Missouri, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Texas, Utah, Virginia and Washington.

title: 2-1-1 Information & Referral Service
content: Search for resources in your community, including emergency shelter, food banks, substance abuse and mental health services, health care, and child and elder care.

title: Joining Forces
content: White House program that asks Americans to get involved in supporting our military's needs in employment, education, wellness and public awareness. Learn how to get involved.

title: Cleaning for Heroes
content: Provides free house cleaning services to disabled or elderly Veterans and their families.

title: National League of Cities (NLC)
content: Represents municipal governments throughout the United States and works to strengthen and promote cities as centers of opportunity, leadership and governance. Topics include transportation and infrastructure, housing and community development and youth, education and families.

title: Military Families United
content: A not-for-profit organization comprised of a grassroots coalition of Gold Star and Blue Star families that support Service Members and Veterans.

title: Angel Flight for Veterans
content: Offers no-cost or reduced-rate patient travel services for Veterans and their families.

title: Way Station Veteran Programs in Maryland
content: Provides Veterans a broad range of services including job training, mentorship, employment referrals, counseling, mental health or substance abuse services, housing and help with VA related issues.

title: America's Child
content: Providing college education and welfare assistance to children whose parents lost their lives in Operation Enduring Freedom in Afghanistan and the Philippines and Operation Iraqi Freedom. Register surviving children to qualify them for services.

title: American Gold Star Mothers, Inc.
content: Provides support to surviving mothers and their families and works with Veterans and other Veteran organizations.

title: Association for Service Disabled Veterans (ASDV)
content: Works to create opportunities for Service Disabled Veterans to achieve and maintain their rehabilitation through enterprise development and managed employment.

title: Coalition for Iraq & Afghanistan Veterans
content: Partnership of organizations that provide services to Operation Enduring Freedom and Operation Iraqi Freedom Veterans and their families.

title: Blue Star Mothers of America, Inc.
content: Provides support for mothers who now have, or have had, children honorably serving in the military.

title: Better Business Bureau (BBB) Military Line
content: Provides Service Members and their families with consumer education and advocacy, including a variety of free consumer services and materials.

title: Bugles Across America
content: Performs live renditions of Taps played by a Bugler at honor and memorial ceremonies.

title: National Family Caregivers Association
content: Provides resources for the more than 50 million Americans who care for loved ones with a chronic illness, disability or the frailties of old age. Includes information on locating senior housing, communicating with family and friends, information on Medicare drug plans, and more.

title: Home Front Hearts
content: Serves the families that serve our country by providing support and resources to the families of Service Members, increasing public awareness of the struggles and sacrifices of military families, and engaging both individuals and businesses in building communities that are responsive to the needs of these families.

title: The Mission Continues
content: Awards fellowships so wounded and disabled Veterans who were injured in Iraq or Afghanistan can serve their communities by volunteering full-time at a local charitable organization.

title: Value of Volunteer Time
content: Calculates the monetary value of volunteer hours donated while caring for Veterans.

title: National 4-H
content: Provides quality educational experiences using research-based curricula for military youth ages 5-19.

title: Volunteer Match
content: Matches volunteers with organizations that provide services to the military community.

title: Volunteer to Give Veterans a Helping Hand
content: Explains the many ways volunteers can offer help to Veterans and their families.

title: Services for Military & Veteran Communities
content: Learn about family support programs, respite care, adult day care and other programs available through Easter Seals.

title: Air Compassion for Veterans (ACV)
content: Provides free air transport for OIF-OEF Veterans and family members for medical evaluation, diagnosis, treatment or rehabilitation.

title: AcademyWomen
content: Supports the professional and personal growth of women from military academies and officer development programs. Provides supplemental sources of education, mentorship resources, leadership development opportunities and advocacy resources.

title: Team Rubicon
content: Unites the skills and experiences of Veterans with first responders to rapidly deploy emergency response teams.

title: Military Outreach USA
content: Serves Service Members, Veterans and their families by connecting them to a network of individuals and faith-based resources in their local community.

title: Wreaths Across America
content: Oversees programs to remember and honor the service and sacrifices of our Veterans, Service Members and their families.

title: Team Red, White & Blue
content: Supports Veterans and their families with physical and social activities. Find a chapter near you.

title: USO San Diego
content: Offers active and retired Service Members and their families travel, care packages, therapy dogs, meals, clothing, housing and access to reintegration services.

title: National Center for Charitable Statistics (NCCS) Data Web
content: Information on accessing data on non-profit organizations. Go right to the public databases or find out what you need to know before you get started.

title: Network for Good
content: Philanthropy site where individuals can donate, volunteer and get involved with the issues they care about.

title: Tips on Charitable Giving
content: Tips on charitable giving from the Better Business Bureau to help donors make wise giving decisions.

title: The Foundation Center 990 Finder
content: Allows you to look up Internal Revenue Service (IRS) Form 990 for non-profit organizations within the United States.

title: American Institute of Philanthropy
content: Helps donors make informed donation decisions with resources including top-rated groups, the Charity Rating Guide and Watchdog Report, tips for giving, frequently asked questions and articles.

title: Better Business Bureau Charity List
content: Evaluates charities based on financial and management practices. Browse National Charity Reports.

title: Charity Navigator
content: Evaluates the financial health of over 5,300 of America's largest charities. Searchable by keyword, category or region.

title: Check Out a Charity
content: A search engine supported by the Better Business Bureau (BBB) that looks up details on businesses and charities.

title: Crimes Against Charitable Americans Act
content: Details the regulation associated with telemarketing rules that stipulates phone solicitation of charitable contributions to be clearly disclosed as the purpose of the call.

title: Federal Trade Commission (FTC) Charity Checklist
content: Ensure that your donation dollars benefit the people and organizations you want to help.

title: GuideStar
content: Database includes all Internal Revenue Service (IRS)-registered tax-deductible charities, comprising over 700,000 organizations. Some listings do not provide full data.

title: IRS Charity List
content: The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) provides a list of organizations eligible to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.

title: IRS Tax Information for Charitable Organizations
content: Information from the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on the life cycle of a public charity and tax exemption requirements.

title: Independent Sector - Wise Giving
content: Tips for protecting yourself and your investment in charities.

title: JustGive Guide
content: Database of screened and approved charities, organized by subject.

title: National Association of State Charity Officials
content: State-by-state contact information and links to charity regulators.

title: Troops First Foundation
content: Find information about initiatives to support wounded warrior care, such as Operation Proper Exit.

title: Computer/Electronic Accommodations Program (CAP)
content: Provides needs assessments, assistive technology (AT) and training free of charge to wounded Service Members in support of their recovery, rehabilitation and transition to employment.

title: Community of Veterans
content: Connects Veterans together to help them transition into civilian life.

title: Warrior Care
content: Provides links to resources for warrior care, including service programs, DoD and VA resources, news and events, and more.

title: Quality of Life Plus
content: Identifies the challenges of those who have been injured and works with teams of university students and faculty to solve these challenges so individuals with disabilities can live, work and play unassisted.

title: Impact A Hero
content: Provides emotional and financial support for severely wounded and disabled Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom troops, including flight and holiday support, a sports and outdoors program and career mentorship.

title: Operation Mend
content: Provides medical services to military personnel wounded during service in Iraq and Afghanistan and offers Buddy Families who share their homes with the Service Members during their time in Los Angeles.

title: G.I. Go Fund
content: Provides transition assistance to Veterans to include educational assistance, emergency financial assistance as well as guidance through the VA process.

title: United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM) Care Coalition
content: Provides resources to support the rehabilitation and reintegrations of wounded warriors in the areas of employment, mental health, family support and benefits.

title: Wounded Warrior Project - Peer Mentoring
content: Provides recovering wounded warriors one-on-one friendships with peer mentors; fellow wounded warriors further along in the recovery process. Peer mentors are also available to visit with warriors’ families, if requested, to serve as role models, helping them visualize what can be achieved through rehabilitation and hard work.

title: Marine Corps Wounded Warrior Regiment (WWR)
content: Provides assistance to wounded, injured and ill marines; sailors attached to or in support of Marine Corps units; and their family members throughout the phases of recovery.

title: Veteran Love
content: Helps military Veterans by providing temporary housing, counseling and emergency financial aid.

title: Army Well-Being Wounded Soldier Information
content: Links to resources for wounded soldiers, including the Wounded Soldier and Family Hotline, which is available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week at 1-800-984-8523.

title: Marine for Life
content: Provides assistance to transitioning Marines with employment, Veterans benefits, education and community information, links to service organizations and more.

title: Federal Recovery Coordinator Program
content: DoD, VA and Department of Health and Human Services program that links seriously wounded and ill Service Members, Veterans and their families to services in support of their recovery, rehabilitation and reintegration.

title: Army Warrior Care & Transition Office
content: Provides strategic direction and develops plans, policies and resources for warrior care initiatives and programs dedicated to the support, care, and healing of wounded, ill and injured soldiers.

title: Air Force Wounded Warrior Program (AFW2)
content: Provides personalized services to combat wounded, ill and injured airmen and their families through regular communication and support for non-medical matters. For more information and assistance call 1-800-581-9437.

title: Army Wounded Warrior Program (AW2)
content: Provides individualized support to severely wounded, injured and ill Army personnel and their families. Services to assist with career, education, finances, health care, insurance, retirement, transition and more are available. For more information and assistance, call 1-800-237-1336 or email  AW2@conus.army.mil.

title: State VA Offices
content: Select a state from the map to find contact information for state VA offices that offer help with services and benefits for Veterans.

title: Challenge America
content: Offers returning and injured Veterans and their families access to community services including recreational and occupational programs.

title: Our Forgotten Warriors
content: Provides family support services, PTSD counseling, emergency funding and reintegrating programs.

title: Strikeouts for Troops
content: Provides injured troops with the comforts of home while they are undergoing treatment at military hospitals across the country.

title: Sentinels of Freedom
content: Offers life scholarships for eligible severely wounded Veterans, which include not only actual scholarships for education, but also housing, new furniture and household supplies, career-placement assistance and training, adaptive vehicles, placement and mentoring at corporations.

title: U.S. Army Warrior Transition Command (WTC)
content: Provides wounded soldiers and their families with information to help them through the healing and transition process. Covers administrative processes, benefits and resources, including career and education training options.

title: Operation Lima Foxtrot
content: Find information about The Lakeshore Foundation's year-round sport, fitness and recreation programs for severely injured members of our Armed Forces.

title: Tempered Steel Inc.
content: Connects wounded warriors with schools, community groups and corporate events to share their personal stories of healing and resiliency.

title: Military Warriors Support Foundation
content: Supports combat wounded heroes and Gold Star  Families as they transition out of the military through home donation, employment assistance and recreational activities.

title: U.S. Army Warrior Transition Command (WTC) Comprehensive Transition Plan
content: Allows Soldiers to customize their recovery process, enabling them to set and reach their personal goals with a six-part interdisciplinary structured process the Soldier builds for him/herself with the support of the WTU cadre.

title: Warrior Navigation and Assistance Program
content: Provides support and guidance to military and civilian health care professionals with treatment, rehabilitation and reintegration of recovering warriors.

title: Navy Safe Harbor
content: Provides non-medical support to seriously wounded, ill, and injured Sailors and Coast Guardsmen, as well as their families. Assists service members throughout their recovery, rehabilitation, and reintegration. For more assistance call 1-877-746-8563 or email safeharbor@navy.mil.

title: Moving Forward
content: Operates a free, on-line educational and life coaching program from the VA that teaches problem solving skills to help better handle life’s challenges.

title: Azalea Charities Aid for Wounded Soldiers
content: Provides comfort and relief items for soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines who are sick, injured or wounded from service in Iraq and Afghanistan.

title: Samaritan's Purse - Operation Heal Our Patriots
content:
Gives 150 wounded Veterans and their spouses spiritual engagement opportunities and through retreats and recreation. Lodging and transportation included.
Applications accepted starting February 1.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center -  Wounded, Ill and Injured Injury Prevention
content: Lists practical tools, educational resources and evidence-based prevention strategies that help keep wounded, ill and injured sailors healthy.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center - Wounded, Ill and Injured Health Promotion
content: Provides evidence-based health promotion programs and services that facilitate readiness and resilience, prevent illness and injury, hasten recovery, and promote lifelong healthy behaviors.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center - Wounded, Ill and Injured Substance Abuse
content: Links to educational materials and resources to help understand the negative effects of binge drinking, misuse or abuse of over-the-counter and prescription medications, and  the dangers of excessive alcohol consumption.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center - Wounded, Ill and Injured Nutrition
content: Details nutritional information and resources dedicated to addressing the role of nutrition for those who have been wounded, ill, and/or injured.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center - Wounded, Ill and Injured Intimacy and Relationships
content: Provides information and resources dedicated to addressing issues impacting relationships, intimacy and the sexual health of those who have been wounded, ill and injured.

title: Navy and Marine Corps Public Health Center - Wounded, Ill and Injured Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder
content: Lists PTSD resources to promote resiliency and build psychological fitness for those recovering from PTSD, as well as information for family members and providers.

title: Marine Corps Wounded Warrior Regiment (WWR) Recovery Care Coordinators
content: Works with wounded, ill or injured Marines and their families to create support networks and develop a Comprehensive Recovery Plan (CRP) whether they are assigned to the Wounded Warrior Regiment or remain with their operational units.

title: Marine Corps Wounded Warrior Regiment (WWR) Call Center
content: Details contact information for the Sergeant Merlin German Wounded Warrior Call Center, WWR Headquarters and both WWR Battalions.

title: Marine Corps Wounded Warrior Regiment (WWR) District Injured Support Coordinators
content: Conduct face-to-face visits and telephone outreach to wounded, ill and injured Marines and their families to support psychological health, legal, benefits, employment, housing and other areas.

title: U.S. Army Warrior Care & Transition Program (WCTP)
content: Enables the Army to evaluate and treat soldiers through a comprehensive, soldier-centric process of medical care, rehabilitation, professional development and achievement of personal goals.

title: Army Personnel Records
content: Provides contact information to acquire military records listed by status of Service Member or Veteran.

title: Checking the Status of Your Request for Military Records
content: Provides instructions for calling (1-314-801-0800), faxing and e-mailing a status request.

title: Coast Guard Personnel Records
content: Provides contact information to acquire military records listed by status of Service Member or Veteran.

title: Information Found on DD Form 214
content: Learn about the Report of Separation. Includes contact information for requesting replacement of military service medals, decorations and awards.

title: Military Service Records for Veterans & Next-of-Kin
content: Find out about requests for Official Military Personnel Files, which must be authorized by original signature. Use the eVetRecs request system or mail in Form SF-180.

title: Army Knowledge Online
content: Provides secure access to Army Web assets, tools and services to soldiers, Army employees, retirees and family members worldwide.

title: National Archives Holdings
content: Provides an overview of records relating to military service held at the National Archives.

title: Navy Personnel Records
content: Find contact information to acquire military records listed by status of Service Member or Veteran.

title: Navy Service Records
content: Explains what can be found inside a Navy service record, the different types of records that are used and responsibility of maintaining records.

title: Office of Freedom of Information
content: Processes Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) requests from the general public, verification of military services and consultations from the Office of the Secretary of Defense and Joint Staff.

title: Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Records Requests
content: Provides access to VA medical records, national cemetery records and benefits records. Click here for information on how to submit a FOIA request.

content: Identifies ways to locate records for Veterans who served in World War II including service records, photographs and casualty lists.

title: Selective Service Records
content: Provides manpower to the military by conducting a draft and includes an online Selective Service registration system.

title: Common Access Card (CAC) RAPIDS Site Locator
content: Visit any of the 1,500+ Real-Time Automated Personnel Identification System (RAPIDS) centers worldwide to obtain your next-generation CAC.

title: Civil War Soldiers & Sailors System
content: Serves as a computerized database containing very basic facts about Service Men who served during the Civil War.

title: Medal of Honor Citations
content: Find in the U.S. Army Center of Military History lists by war of the entire transcripts of Medal of Honor Citations for more than 3,400 Service Members.

title: Military Resources
content: Locate military reference material, military history and research, and specific resources by branch of service or by military engagement from the Archives Library Information Center (ALIC).

title: Army Long Term Family Case Management
content: Assists families of fallen soldiers with information on survivor benefits, obtaining service records, soldier services, support programs and more.

content: Provides access for most Veterans and next-of-kin to obtain free copies of their DD Form 214 (Report of Separation) and other military and medical records.

content: Access DD Form 149, Application for Correction of Military Records and Form 293, Application for the Review of Discharge or Dismissal from the Armed Forces of the United States.

title: Air Force Personnel Records

title: Marine Corps Personnel Records
content: Provides contact information to acquire military records listed by status of Service Member or Veteran.

content: Documents a Marine's career from entrance into the Marine Corps or Marine Corps Reserve, until severance by discharge, retirement, resignation or death.

title: Military Personnel Records
content: Provides access to official files, including Active Duty health records, clinical records and medical treatment records.

content: Topics include forms, locating Service Members and Veterans, privacy protections and more. Includes e-mail, phone and fax contact information for the customer service center.

content: Gives information on how the National Archives protects files from disclosure to unauthorized individuals.

title: Army Board for Correction of Military Records
content: Provides the highest level of administrative review within the Department of the Army to correct errors in or remove injustices from Army military records.

title: Army Grade Determination Review Board
content: Determines the highest grade in which a Soldier served satisfactorily.

title: Alabama Emergency Management Agency
content: Assists with the needs of disaster victims as well as local governments in preparedness, response and recovery.  Learn about your disaster risks and preparing your response effort.

title: Disabled Sports USA (DS/USA) - Alabama
content: Locate DS/USA chapters in Alabama. Offers sports rehabilitation programs, including winter skiing, aquatic sports, competition and special sports events, to anyone with a permanent disability. The Warfighter Sports program serves wounded warriors, including those injured in the Iraq and Afghanistan wars, through sports rehabilitation programs in military hospitals and communities across the U.S.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representing states in Washington DC and developing policy reports on innovative state programs.

title: Alabama's Operation Grateful Heart
content: Provides programs and services to ensure that all military personnel and their families in the State of Alabama receive appropriate recognition, tangible support and neighborly care.

title: Lakeshore Foundation
content: Promotes independence for persons with physically disabling conditions and opportunities to pursue active healthy lifestyles. Lima Foxtrot Programs for Injured Military include a number of weekend-long camps that bring injured military personnel and their families from across the country to Alabama.

title: Alabama Disabilities Advocacy Program (ADAP)

title: Alabama Ability Loan Program

title: Alabama Relay
content: Provides a full telephone interpreting service between people who can hear and those who are deaf, hard-of-hearing, deaf-blind or speech-disabled.

title: Alabama Consumers' Guide to Legal Help
content: Provides Alabama resources for finding legal advice or representation, hiring or using a lawyer, and representing yourself or learning about the law.

title: National Guard Family Program - Local Community Resource Finder
content: Lists family and other resources available to Guardsmen and their families, and provides contact information.  For more specific information, select the relevant state and/or city, and choose a category or resource.

title: Wyoming Directory of Pro Bono Legal Programs
content: Offers a directory of pro bono legal programs serving residents of Wyoming.

title: Wyoming Consumers' Guide to Legal Help
content: Provides Wyoming resources for finding legal advice or representation, hiring or using a lawyer, and representing yourself or learning about the law.

title: Military/Veteran License Plates
content: Provides information on obtaining Wyoming's special military/Veteran license plates.

title: Public Health Emergency Resources for Wyoming
content: Coordinates effective responses to bioterrorism and other public health emergencies through the Wyoming Department of Health.

title: Wyoming National Guard
content: Provides information, resources and news for and about the Wyoming National Guard.

title: Oregon Trail State Veterans Cemetery
content: Provides burial space for Veterans of Wyoming.

title: Wyoming Military Campgrounds
content: Provides list of recreational travel and outdoor opportunities in Wyoming.

title: Army Family Readiness Groups (FRGs) in Wyoming
content: Provides a list of Army FRGs located in Wyoming, which provide a connection to unit information for spouses and other family members.

title: American Red Cross of Wyoming
content: Provides Armed Forces with emergency communications that link them with their families back home, access to financial assistance from the military aid societies, counseling, referral to community resources and assistance to Veterans. Call (307) 638-8906 to access these and other services.

title: Pro Bono Legal Resources for Veterans
content: Find contact information for free legal resources nationally and state by state.

title: Federal Voting Assistance Program - Wyoming
content: Find information on voting for Service Members, their families and citizens living outside the United States.  Register to vote, request an absentee ballot and more.

title: 2-1-1 Wyoming
content: Call 2-1-1 for information about important health and human services in Wyoming. 2-1-1 connects you to programs and services that can help you access health care, housing, help paying utilities, transportation, mental health counseling and more.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representation in Washington, DC on key issues and developing policy reports on innovative state programs. NGA addresses areas that include education, health, and technology and welfare reform.

title: Federal Voting Assistance Program - American Samoa
content: Find information on voting for Service Members, their families and citizens living outside the United States.  Register to vote, request an absentee ballot and more.

title: Wounded Warrior Battalion West
content: Provides and facilitates assistance to wounded, ill and injured Marines and Sailors attached to or in support of Marine units, and their family members throughout the phases of recovery.

title: Naval Base Guam Navy Fleet & Family Support Center (NFFSC)
content: Provides services to sailors and families in Guam and the Mariana Islands. Services may include family support groups, domestic abuse prevention, Ombudsman program, personal finance management, sexual assault prevention and transition assistance.

title: Office of the Governor of Guam
content: Provides news and information from the office of the Governor of Guam. Includes an online job bank.

title: National Guard Family Program - Local Community Resource Finder
content: Lists family and other resources available to Guardsmen and their families, and provides contact information.  For more specific information, users can select Guam and/or a particular city, and choose a specific category of resource.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representing states in Washington, DC on key issues and developing policy reports on innovative state programs. NGA addresses areas that include education, health, technology and welfare reform.

title: Emergency Preparedness for Guam
content: Alerts communities and coordinates emergency responses to damage, injury and loss of life and property due to natural, technological or man-made disasters and emergencies. The preparedness site provides information for preparing emergency plans to protect your family.

title: Public Health Emergency Resources for Guam
content: Coordinates effective responses to bioterrorism and other public health emergencies through the Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services.  The Division of Public Health provides information on local health resources.

title: Guam Food Stamp Program
content: Helps low-income people and families buy the food they need for good health. You can apply for benefits by completing a state application form.

title: Federal Voting Assistance Program - Guam
content: Find information on voting for Service Members, their families and citizens living outside the United States.  Register to vote, request an absentee ballot and more.

title: Emergency Preparedness Resources for Puerto Rico
content: Links to emergency preparedness information for the Southeastern/Altantic Region.

content: Provides a list of Puerto Rico ESGR Committee contacts. Each committee has trained volunteer ombudsmen who help resolve issues between employers and their employees who serve in the National Guard and Reserve. Services may include "Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act (USERRA) information, informal mediation and referral services to resolve conflicts.

title: Puerto Rico Directory of Pro Bono Legal Programs
content: Links to a directory of Pro Bono Legal Programs serving residents of Puerto Rico.

title: Puerto Rico Consumers' Guide to Legal Help
content: Provides Puerto Rico resources for finding legal advice or representation, hiring or using a lawyer, and representing yourself or learning about the law.

title: Association of the United States Army (AUSA) - Puerto Rico Chapters
content: Links to Puerto Rico Chapters of AUSA which keeps soldiers up-to-date on the latest equipment, technology and professional development activities.

title: U.S. Armed Forces Legal Assistance - Puerto Rico Offices
content: List of military legal assistance offices in Puerto Rico.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representing states in Washington, DC on key issues and developing policy reports on innovative state programs. NGA addresses areas that include education, health, technology and welfare reform.  Visit the NGA Web site for information about Puerto Rico government.

title: Puerto Rico Transition Assistance Advisor (TAA)
content: Find contact information for your territory's transition assistance advisor.

content: Works to strengthen and promote cities as centers of opportunity, leadership and governance.  NLC also provides contact information for cities and towns in Puerto Rico to connect you to the programs and services they offer in your community.

title: Federal Voting Assistance Program - Puerto Rico
content: Find information on voting for Service Members, their families and citizens living outside the United States.  Register to vote, request an absentee ballot and more.

title: Operation Military Kids - Virgin Islands
content: Provides support to Army installations and geographically dispersed military youth who are affected by the global war on terrorism.

title: Virgin Islands Transition Assistance Advisor (TAA)
content: Assists Service Members in obtaining Veteran benefits and health care services.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representing states in Washington, DC on key issues and developing policy reports on innovative state programs. NGA addresses areas that include education, health, technology and welfare reform.  Visit NGAs Web site for information about Virgin Islands territorial government.

title: Virgin Islands Employer Support of the Guard & Reserve (ESGR) Committee Contact List
content: Provides a list of Virgin Islands ESGR Committee contacts. Each committee has trained volunteer ombudsmen who help resolve issues between employers and their employees who serve in the National Guard and Reserve. Services may include Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act (USERRA) information, informal mediation and referral services to resolve conflicts.

title: Disability Rights Center of the Virgin Islands
content: Provides free legal representation and other advocacy services to people with disabilities in the Virgin Islands.

title: Virgin Islands Consumers' Guide to Legal Help
content: Provides Virgin Islands resources for finding legal advice or representation, hiring or using a lawyer, and representing yourself or learning about the law.

title: Virgin Islands Food Stamp Program
content: Helps low-income people and families buy the food they need for good health.

title: Federal Voting Assistance Program - Virgin Islands
content: Find information on voting for Service Members, their families and citizens living outside the United States.  Register to vote, request an absentee ballot and more.

title: National Governors Association (NGA)
content: Provides governors with services that include representing states in Washington, DC on key issues and developing policy reports on innovative state programs. NGA addresses areas that include education, health and technology and welfare reform.

title: Easter Seals' Military & Veterans Initiative
content: Offers Service Members, Veterans and family members services to help in transitioning to civilian life.

title: GI Go Fund Transition Center
content: Offers transition assistance to Veterans of Operation Enduring Freedom and Operation Iraqi Freedom, as well as assistance with mental wellness, employment, education, events and navigating the VA system.

title: Marine for Life
content: Assists transitioning Marines with employment, Veterans benefits, education and community information, and provides links to service organizations.

title: United States Welcome Home Foundation
content: Program provides outreach, education and training, reintegration and wellness support programs to returning Veterans.

title: VA Information for Returning Service Members
content: Learn about benefits, resources and programs offered by the VA for  Veterans who served in Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF) and Operation  Iraqi Freedom (OIF).

title: Our Military
content: Offers a one-stop location for military and their families to find assistance ranging from training and employment to financial help, free airline tickets, computers, care packages and much more.

title: Cleaning for Heroes
content: Provides free house cleaning services to disabled or elderly Veterans and their families.

title: American Legion - Heroes to Hometowns
content: Provides transition assistance to severely injured Service Members by establishing a support network and coordinating resources on his or her behalf.

title: Fostering Safety, Health & Preparedness
content: Offers advice for returning service men and women on military transitions, disaster preparedness and routine health.

title: Military Families on the Move - Tips for Keeping Your Family Healthy
content: Offers advice for Service Members on how to make their family's health care transition go more smoothly when moving, especially when deploying or returning from deployment.

title: Becoming a Couple Again
content: Brochure published by the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences that explains ways to create a shared sense of purpose as a couple after returning from deployment.

title: Air Force Crossroads Pre-Deployment Guide
content: Answers questions on deployment as well as the reunion of friends and family. Includes information on health and wellness for Service Members and their families.

title: U.S. Army Europe Reintegration Programs
content: A guide to help families cope with the stress and challenges associated with reintegration and reunion.

title: Reuniting with Your Loved One - Helpful Advice for Families
content: Access a fact sheet that provides information on ways to enhance your homecoming and communication during the holidays when a Service Member returns home.

title: ONE Freedom
content: Provides education and training for Service Members and families regarding responses to stress, and offers self-guided tools for increasing personal resiliency.

title: Project New Hope
content: Provides free retreats in a camp-like setting for Veterans and their families.

title: Community of Veterans
content: Connects Veterans together to help them transition into civilian life.

title: Battlemind Armor for the Mind
content: Provides video resources for soldiers and family members on handling the stresses of deployment and transitioning home. Includes specific resources for youth coping with military deployment.

title: Operation Healthy Reunions - How to Get Back to Normal
content: Provides tips to help Service Members through the transition of returning home after military duty.

title: Mental Health Resources for Returning Veterans & Their Families
content: Access information from the Substance Abuse & Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA) about prevention, treatment and recovery support for mental health and substance use disorders.

title: Helping Kids Deal with Deployment
content: Provides guidance on how to cope with the challenges and adjustments that children and families often face during a deployment.

title: afterdeployment.org - Balancing Your Life
content: Focuses on the importance of a balanced life when work and home schedules are hectic and demanding. Utilizes the "mind-body" model and engaging exercises to help achieve more balance in life.

title: afterdeployment.org
content: Provides a variety of behavioral health information for Service Members, Veterans and military families.

title: afterdeployment.org - Living with Physical Injuries
content: Offers ways to manage the immediate and long-term aspects of coping with a physical injury attained during deployment.

title: afterdeployment.org - Sleeping Better
content: Teaches strategies that help with sleep problems, even frequent nightmares, which can be common following a deployment.

title: Staying Healthy Where You Live
content: Describes how to manage barriers to care. Learn when it's time to seek out a professional and what type of provider to contact in your area.

title: afterdeployment.org - Dealing with Depression
content: Learn about the causes and signs of depression. Offers an assessment, an electronic-library, game-based simulations and narrator-guided self-help workshops.

title: afterdeployment.org - Spiritual Fitness
content: Learn how spiritual well-being can help you both cope with and understand your deployment experiences.

title: afterdeployment.org - Links, Books, Blogs & Podcasts
content: Offers a number of links to external resources on each of the 12 After Deployment programs that are designed to help soldiers adjust after deployment.

title: afterdeployment.org - Improving Relationships
content: Tools to help Service Members improve their relationships with family and friends. Offers an assessment, an electronic-library, game-based simulations and narrator-guided self-help workshops.

title: MyVetwork
content: Learn about an online community dedicated specifically for use by all U.S. Military, whether active duty, Veterans or retired, and their families and friends, too, to share useful, timely information in video format on subjects of importance to them.

title: afterdeployment.org - Adjusting to War Memories
content: Provides tools to deal with difficult deployment reminders that may occur in the daily lives of Service Members or Veterans. Offers an assessment, an electronic-library, game-based simulations and narrator-guided self-help workshops.

title: afterdeployment.org - Overcoming Anger
content: Recognize anger cues and learn strategies to manage anger. Offers an assessment, an electronic-library, game-based simulations and narrator-guided self-help workshops.

title: afterdeployment.org - Handling Stress
content: Teaches Service Members how to assess their levels of stress and offers stress reduction exercises.

title: afterdeployment.org - Succeeding at Work
content: Provides information on how to deal with on-the-job problems and succeed at work after a deployment. Offers an assessment, an electronic-library, game-based simulations and narrator-guided self-help workshops.

title: Wingman Project
content: The goal of the Wingman Project is to eliminate Warfighter and family member suicide through human outreach, media and training.

title: The 4E Network
content: Educates and informs the community about the challenges facing wounded soldiers returning home from Iraq and Afghanistan, as well as offers support and recreational programs.

title: Returning from the War Zone - A Guide for Military Personnel
content: Helps Service Members and Veterans understand what to expect when returning from a war zone, how to handle the transition, the signs of post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and where to go for help.

title: Safety, Health & Preparedness for Military Families
content: Access a fact sheet offered by the Uniformed Services University of Health Sciences that provides advice and reminders for military families about the deployment cycle, routine health and family preparedness for disaster.

title: Vets Journey Home
content: Discover a unique weekend program for Veterans, designed to help heal the emotional wounds of military service.

title: Grace After Fire
content: Connect with women Veterans and clinical providers who specialize in treating mental health, substance abuse and trauma issues of women who have served.

title: Service Women's Action Network
content: Connects women Veterans to mentors for personal and professional guidance, legal advice and counseling services.

title: An Online Directory of Resources for the Military Community - Warrior Gateway
content: Connects all members of the military community, their spouses and families to the resources they need for transitioning to civilian life.

title: Coming Home Project
content: Offers programs that address the mental, emotional, spiritual and relationship challenges faced by Veterans and families before, during and after deployment.

title: Camp Lejeune Deployment & Reunion Programs
content: Find pre-deployment, deployment and homecoming support services for Service Members and families at Naval Hospital Camp Lejeune.

title: VHA Directive 2012-034 - Welcome Home Events for Returning Service Members
content: Identifies requirements for "Welcome Home" events for Service Members and Veterans who served in Operation Enduring Freedom, Operation Iraqi Freedom or Operation New Dawn.

title: Silent Siren
content: Seeks to establish a PTSD Registry, PTSD training for emergency services personnel and military families, and the implementation of a family/caregiver support system.

title: Veterans Alumni Association
content: Get information on locating friends and fellow Veterans you have served with in the Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines or Coast Guard.

title: Navy Returning Warrior Workshop (RWW)
content: Outlines workshops available to sailors who deployed as individual augmentees and their families upon returning home. Also maintains a schedule of RWW dates and locations.

title: Yellow Ribbon Reintegration Program - EventPLUS
content: Enables community partners, vendors, staff, Reserve Component Service Members and their families to find and register for upcoming Yellow Ribbon Reintegration Program events.

title: Yellow Ribbon Reintegration Program - Agenda Builder
content: Offers Yellow Ribbon Reintegration Program (YRRP) event planners and staff a simple interface to build, edit, and publish agendas.

title: Veteran - Civilian Dialogue (VCD)
content: Three hour live events with equal numbers of Veterans and civilians in facilitated conversations around the impact of war upon both groups. Find out more about VCD and a calendar of upcoming events.

title: Coaching Into Care
content: Provides coaching to the family members and friends of Veterans to assist them in supporting their loved ones during post-deployment and ongoing reintegration. This is a national clinical service providing information and assistance. For confidential help, call 1-888-823-7458.

title: Vets4Warriors
content: Provides National Guard and all reserve component members with the ability to speak with counselors on the phone or online. 1-855-838-8255

title: Honor Them Foundation
content: Utilizes vacant timeshares and unbooked cruises to send Veterans and their families to resorts or on cruises at no charge.

title: Operation Vacation
content: Reunites soldiers with their families on free vacations in the Roaring Fork Valley and Grand County, Colorado and in Dallas and Austin, Texas.

title: Operation Welcome Homes
content: Provides free vacations to Iraq and Afghanistan Veterans and their families.

title: Canine Assistants
content: Provides service dogs free of charge to any child or adult in the United States who has a physical disability, seizure condition or other special need. Download an application.

title: Patriot Paws
content: Trains service dogs to provide assistance to disabled Veterans.

title: Southeastern Guide Dogs, Inc.
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs with blind and visually impaired Veterans at no charge. Other programs include placement of dogs to help mitigate the effects of PTSD. Intensive training and lifetime follow-up support is provided to each partnership.

title: Pilot Dogs, Inc.
content: Trains and places guide dogs, and provides formal and intensive on-site training for individuals and guide dogs.

title: Fidos for Freedom, Inc.
content: Provides trained Service Dogs or Hearing Dogs to people in the Maryland and Washington, D.C. area who have physical disabilities or are deaf or hard-of-hearing. Includes ongoing support services and training.

title: Saint Francis Service Dogs
content: Provides professionally trained service dogs to assist wounded soldiers. Service dogs for Veterans do all the tasks required of a service dog, as well as offer relief for PTSD and other combat-related issues.

title: Eye Dog Foundation for the Blind
content: Trains and provides German Shepherd guide dogs to blind and visually impaired individuals free of charge. Provides intensive training for individuals and guide dogs.

title: Canines for Combat Veterans
content: Program of NEADS that trains and provides assistance dogs to Veterans with hearing, mobility and other disabilities.

title: Guide Dog Foundation for the Blind, Inc.
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs with individuals with visual impairments.

title: Guiding Eyes for the Blind, Inc.
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs, and provides formal and intensive on-site training for individuals and guide dogs.

title: Leader Dogs for the Blind
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs, and provides formal training of individuals and guide dogs. Extended services include training on cane and GPS, as well as career development.

title: NEADS: Dogs for Deaf or Disabled Americans
content: Trains and provides hearing and service dogs to individuals with hearing impairments and other disabilities.

title: Assistance Dogs International
content: Works to improve the training, placement and utilization of assistance dogs, including guide dogs for people with visual impairments, hearing dogs for people with hearing impairments and service dogs for people with other disabilities.

title: Canine Companions for Independence
content: Provides highly trained assistance dogs and ongoing support to ensure quality partnerships between individuals and their service dogs.

title: Paws for Purple Hearts
content: Teaches Veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and other cognitive and emotional disabilities how to train service dogs for other Veterans with physical disabilities.  A program of Bergen University for Canine Studies.

title: Paws with a Cause
content: Trains assistance dogs for people with a range of disabilities, and provides lifetime support to encourage independence.

title: Fidelco Guide Dog Foundation
content: Breeds, trains and places German Shepherd guide dogs, and provides one-on-one in-community training of individuals and guide dogs.

title: The Seeing Eye, Inc.
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs, and provides formal and intensive on-site training for individuals and guide dogs.  The initial fee is $150, with $50 for each subsequent visit.

title: Freedom Guide Dogs for the Blind
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs, and provides one-on-one in-community training of individuals and guide dogs.

title: Information About Service Dogs for People with Psychiatric Disabilities
content: Describes a number of tasks a service dog could be trained to do that would serve to mitigate conditions such as panic disorder, post-traumatic stress disorder and depression.

title: Service Dog Project, Inc.
content: Donates large trained dogs to assist patients with balance and  mobility challenges such as those resulting from Multiple Sclerosis, Parkinson's and war injuries. Preference is given to Veterans and their families.

title: Freedom Service Dogs
content: Rescues dogs and trains them to assist Veterans and Service Members with mobility impairments, PTSD and TBI. Trained dogs are matched with and donated to Service Members/Veterans who are taught how to work with the dog. Freedom Service Dogs supports the client-dog team for its lifetime.

title: Guide Dogs for the Blind
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs.  Provides innovative partnership training at campuses in California and Oregon to acclimate individual and guide dog to each other.

title: Guide Dogs of America
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs and delivers an on-site training course to acclimate individuals with their guide dogs.

title: Guide Dogs of the Desert
content: Breeds, trains and places guide dogs, and provides formal and intensive on-site training for individuals and guide dogs.

title: Pets 2 Vets
content: Provides sheltered animals with active duty military personnel, Veterans and emergency first responders recovering from the stress and trauma of service.

title: Commonly Asked Questions About Service Animals
content: Answers questions such as "What is a service animal?", "How can I tell if an animal is really a service animal and not just a pet?" and "I have always had a clearly posted 'no pets' policy at my establishment. Do I still have to allow service animals in?"

title: America's Vet Dogs
content: Trains and places guide dogs and service dogs with Veterans who have visual impairments or other disabilities.

title: Service Dogs for the Wounded Veterans Program
content: Provides service dogs to Veterans who are amputees, use a wheelchair or require a dog trained to assist with PTSD.

title: Veterans Moving Forward
content: Provides service dogs, at no cost, to Veterans with physical and mental health challenges, including those suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder and traumatic brain injuries.

title: 4 Paws Veterans Service Dog Program
content: Provides service/assistance dogs to Veterans who have a mobility problem or hearing loss resulting from combat injuries to help them lead a more independent life.  Air Compassion for Veterans will provide round trip airfare free of charge for any financially stressed, wounded Veteran, so they can fly to Xenia, Ohio to work with and become accustomed to their service dog.

title: Paws4Vets
content: Provides qualified Veterans and Active Duty military and their dependents with certified assistance dogs custom trained to fit their individual requirements and needs.

title: Service Animals & the Air Carrier Access Act (ACAA)
content: Watch this Disability Law Lowdown American Sign Language video podcast to learn about your rights and responsibilities under the ACAA when taking a service animal on an airplane with you.

title: Puppies Behind Bars
content: Povides service dogs to Veterans returning home from Iraq (OIF) and Afghanistan (OEF) who have suffered a physical injury, traumatic brain injury (TBI) or exhibit Post Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD).

title: K9s for Warriors
content: Raises awareness and funds to provide service dogs to wounded Service Members.

title: Freedom Dogs - Short Term and Permanent Service Dogs for Veterans
content: Offers short term and permanent placement of Specialty Service Dogs with troops returning from war with PTSD and physical limitations at no cost to military personnel.

title: Shepherds for Lost Sheep
content: Trains service dogs to enhance the lives of Veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) or traumatic brain injury (TBI).
